    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-11-05T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-11-05T10:00:00-05:00" n="491"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d491">
                <head>491. <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Executive Committee record of
                    action, November 5<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d491fn1">Aerial
                        reconnaissance missions; <persName corresp="#p_MJJ_1"
                            >McCloy</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_KVV_1">Kuznetsov</persName>
                        discussions at UN. Top Secret. 1 p. Kennedy Library, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSF_1">NSF</gloss>, Meetings and Memoranda Series, Executive
                        Committee, Meetings, Vol. II, Meetings 17–24.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <idno type="document-identifier">Meeting No. 20</idno>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1962-11-05T10:00:00">November 5, 1962, 10
                            a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d491-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d491-1"/>
                <p>1. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MJA_1">McCone</persName> presented the intelligence
                    summary, including a comparison of our estimate of the number of Soviet missiles
                    and missile sites in Cuba with figures given by Soviet representative <persName
                        corresp="#p_KVV_1">Kuznetsov</persName> to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MJJ_1"
                        >McCloy</persName> yesterday.</p>
                <p>2. Secretary <persName corresp="#p_MRS_1">McNamara</persName> reported on the
                    aerial reconnaissance missions of yesterday and those planned for today. The
                    President authorized specific high level and low level flights for today. It was
                    agreed that there would be no release today to the press of either pictures or
                    information obtained from yesterday’s flights.</p>
                <p>3. There was a discussion of policy questions raised during the <persName
                        corresp="#p_MJJ_1">McCloy</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_KVV_1"
                        >Kuznetsov</persName> conversations yesterday. Among these are: a permanent
                        <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> presence in Cuba, including the
                    possibility of some <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> inspection in the U.S.;
                    the continuance of U.S. or <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> aerial
                    reconnaissance flights; the elimination of the <gloss target="#t_IL28_1"
                        >IL–28</gloss> bombers from Cuba; the guarantee that no Soviet submarine
                    base will be established in Cuba; and the relationship of a system to guarantee
                    that Soviet missiles will not be reintroduced into Cuba to the implementation of
                    the conditional U.S. pledge not to invade Cuba.</p>
                <p>4. A cable will be sent to <persName corresp="#p_MJJ_1">McCloy</persName> giving
                    our answers to questions raised by <persName corresp="#p_KVV_1"
                        >Kuznetsov</persName>. A final U.S. position is to be prepared following a
                    report on the <persName corresp="#p_MAI_1">Mikoyan</persName>-Castro talks.</p>
                <p>5. The President scheduled the next Executive Committee meeting at 5:00 PM
                    Tuesday.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_BM_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_BM_1">McGeorge Bundy</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
